      <h3>Intended Use</h3>
      <p>The TS 60 KEB plunge-cut saw is designed for sawing wood, materials similar to wood, gypsum and cement-bonded fibre materials, and plastics. With special Festool saw blades, it can also saw unhardened ferrous and non-ferrous metals. Materials containing asbestos must not be processed. Do not use cutting or abrasive wheels.</p>

      <h3>Saw Blade Requirements</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Saw blades per EN 847-1</li>
        <li>Diameter: 6-5/8" (168 mm)</li>
        <li>Cutting width: 5/64" (1.8 mm)</li>
        <li>Locating bore: 25/32" (20 mm)</li>
        <li>Standard blade thickness: 3/64" (1.2 mm)</li>
        <li>Suitable for speeds up to 9,500 min<sup>-1</sup></li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Blade Changes</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> Always disconnect the mains plug from the socket before performing any work on the machine. Wear protective gloves when handling insertion tools.
      </div>

      <h3>Removing the Saw Blade</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Swivel the saw to 0&deg; and adjust to maximum cutting depth.</li>
        <li>Turn the lever [4-3] as far as it will go. Operate the lever only when the saw is at a standstill.</li>
        <li>Push the saw unit down until it engages.</li>
        <li>Lay the saw on its side on a stable base with the saw blade side upwards.</li>
        <li>Loosen the screw [4-5] using the Allen key [4-2].</li>
        <li>Remove the saw blade [4-6].</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Cleaning the Feeler Unit</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> Any contamination of the feeler unit may impair the KickbackStop function and prevent the saw blade from being stopped.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Hold the saw unit securely by its handle, close the lever [4-3], and press the saw unit all the way down.</li>
        <li>Release the lever [4-3] again and click the saw unit into place.</li>
        <li>Clean the feeler unit [4-9] by blowing it out or using a brush.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Inserting a New Saw Blade</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> Check screws and flange for contamination. Only use clean and undamaged parts. The direction of rotation of the saw blade [4-8] and saw [4-4] must match. Serious injuries may occur if they do not.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Hold the saw unit securely by its handle and turn the lever [4-3] as far as it will go.</li>
        <li>Push the saw unit down until it engages.</li>
        <li>Insert the new saw blade with the correct rotation direction.</li>
        <li>Insert the outer flange [4-7] so the pulling peg engages in the recess of the inner flange.</li>
        <li>Tighten the screw [4-5].</li>
        <li>Hold the saw unit by its handle, close the lever [4-3], and guide the saw unit back upwards.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Selecting the Saw Blade</h3>
      <p>Festool saw blades are identified by a colored ring indicating the intended material:</p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Yellow</th><td>Wood</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Red</th><td>Laminate, mineral material, HPL/Trespa</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Green</th><td>Plaster- and cement-bonded chipboard and fibreboard</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Blue</th><td>Aluminum, plastic</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Depth &amp; Bevel Adjustments</h2>

      <h3>Adjusting the Cutting Depth</h3>
      <p>The cutting depth is set at the cutting depth stop [2-1], adjustable from 0 to 2-7/16" (0&ndash;62 mm). The saw unit can be pushed downwards as far as the set cutting depth. Maximum cutting depth with a guide rail is 2-1/4" (57 mm).</p>

      <h3>Adjusting the Cutting Angle (0&deg; to 45&deg;)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Open the rotary knobs [3-1].</li>
        <li>Swivel the saw unit to the desired cutting angle [3-4].</li>
        <li>Close the rotary knobs [3-1].</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Both the 0&deg; and 45&deg; positions are factory-set and can be readjusted by customer service. When making angled cuts, slide the viewing window/splinter guard to the highest position.</p>

      <h3>Undercuts (-1&deg; and 47&deg;)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Swivel the saw unit to the end position (0&deg; or 45&deg;) as described above.</li>
        <li>For 47&deg; undercuts, push the slide [3-3] on the front swivelling segment downwards.</li>
        <li>For -1&deg; undercuts, push the slide [3-2] on the plate forwards.</li>
        <li>The saw unit engages in the -1&deg;/47&deg; position.</li>
        <li>Close the rotary knobs [3-1].</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Speed Control</h3>
      <p>Continuously adjust the speed within the range using the adjusting wheel [1-8]. Recommended speed settings by material:</p>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Material</th><th>Speed Setting</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Solid wood (hard, soft)</td><td>6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Chipboard and hardboard</td><td>3&ndash;6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Laminated wood, blockboard, veneered/laminated panels</td><td>6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Laminate, mineral materials</td><td>4&ndash;6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plaster-/cement-bonded chipboard and fibreboard</td><td>1&ndash;3</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Aluminum panels and profiles up to 19/32" (15 mm)</td><td>4&ndash;6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plastics, fibre-reinforced plastics, paper and fabric</td><td>3&ndash;5</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Acrylic glass</td><td>4&ndash;5</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Electronics</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Overload protection:</strong> Electronic overload protection stops the motor under extreme load. Remove the load, then switch on again to restart.</li>
        <li><strong>Electronic brake:</strong> The saw blade stops electronically within approximately two seconds of switching off.</li>
        <li><strong>Temperature cut-out:</strong> Power is reduced if the motor overheats. The tool continues at reduced power to cool the motor, then resumes full power automatically.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Guide Rail Usage</h2>
      <p>The guide rail enables clean, accurate cuts while protecting the workpiece surface from damage. In conjunction with accessories, exact angled cuts, mitre cuts, and fitting work can be completed.</p>

      <h3>Setting Up the Guide Rail</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Adjust the guide play between the saw table and the guide rail using the two adjustable jaws [11-1].</li>
        <li>Clamps [11-5] can be used to secure the guide rail for safer working conditions.</li>
        <li>Always push the saw forwards [11-2] and never toward yourself.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Bedding In the Guide Rail Splinter Guard</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Set the machine speed to 6.</li>
        <li>Place the machine at the rear end of the guide rail with the complete guide plate.</li>
        <li>Switch on the machine.</li>
        <li>Push down the machine slowly to the maximum preset cutting depth and cut along the full length of the splinter guard without stopping.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>The edge of the splinter guard now corresponds exactly to the cutting edge. Position the guide rail on a test piece of wood for this process.</p>

      <h3>Cross Cutting Guide Rail</h3>
      <p>The FSK cross cutting guide rail is designed for sawing wood and panel materials. It enables precise and clean cuts, and angled cuts can be performed simply with repeat accuracy. The saw automatically moves back to the initial position after sawing. Refer to the FSK operating manual for detailed instructions.</p>

      <h2>Splinterguard</h2>
      <p>The splinter guard (green) [5-2] improves the quality of the cutting edge on the upper side of the workpiece during 0&deg; cuts.</p>

      <h3>Installing the Splinter Guard</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Insert the splinter guard [5-2].</li>
        <li>Screw the rotary knob [5-1] through the hole into the viewing window.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="warning">
        <strong>CAUTION:</strong> Only use the rotary knob supplied with your plunge-cut saw. The rotary knob from another saw may be too long and jam the saw blade.
      </div>

      <h3>Bedding In the Splinter Guard</h3>
      <p>You must bed in the splinter guard before first use:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Set the machine to maximum cutting depth.</li>
        <li>Set the machine speed to 6.</li>
        <li>Place the machine on a test piece of wood and make a cut to bed in the splinter guard.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>KickbackStop</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> The KickbackStop does not guarantee complete protection against a kickback. Always concentrate on your work and follow all safety instructions.
      </div>

      <p>A kickback while working may cause the saw to lift unintentionally. The feeler wedge [8-1] detects unintentional lifting of the saw from the workpiece or rail and triggers quick-acting braking of the saw blade, reducing the risk of a kickback.</p>

      <h3>Status LED Indicators</h3>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Green</th><td>KickbackStop function is active.</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Orange</th><td>KickbackStop function is deactivated.</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Flashing Orange</th><td>KickbackStop is not active. The saw was started before the feeler wedge was pressed against the workpiece or guide rail, or the saw plate is not level. Reposition the saw level to activate.</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Flashing Red</th><td>KickbackStop function has been triggered.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h3>Unintentional Triggering</h3>
      <p>Working without a guide rail on an uneven workpiece may cause the KickbackStop to trigger unintentionally. If there is a recess in the workpiece, the feeler wedge position corresponds to a lift condition. In this case, it may be necessary to deactivate the KickbackStop function.</p>

      <h3>After KickbackStop Has Been Triggered</h3>
      <p><strong>If triggered by a kickback:</strong></p>
      <ol>
        <li>Determine and eliminate the reason for lifting.</li>
        <li>Check the machine and feeler wedge for damage.</li>
        <li>Check the KickbackStop function.</li>
      </ol>
      <p><strong>If triggered unintentionally:</strong></p>
      <ol>
        <li>Release the on/off switch and wait until the status LED stops flashing.</li>
        <li>Determine whether the triggering was unintentional or an actual kickback.</li>
        <li>Try to continue with the KickbackStop active. Only deactivate if the workpiece is too uneven.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Deactivating the KickbackStop</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Press the KickbackStop function OFF button.</li>
        <li>Press and hold the on/off switch within ten seconds.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>The function remains deactivated until the on/off switch is next released. The KickbackStop can only be deactivated before the saw is switched on.</p>

      <h3>Testing the KickbackStop Function</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> Risk of injury from a protruding saw blade. Carry out function testing on the guide rail. Before testing, remove the saw blade and set cutting depth to 0 mm (FS).
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Set cutting depth to 0 mm (FS) and place the machine on the guide rail.</li>
        <li>Switch on the machine.</li>
        <li>Press the KickbackStop OFF button four times at intervals of at least 0.5 seconds within five seconds.</li>
        <li>The status LED flashes alternately red and green.</li>
        <li>Within 15 seconds, press the saw unit down, then lift the machine at the rear and lower it again.</li>
        <li>A signal sounds and the status LED lights up green, confirming fault-free operation.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>If no signal sounds and the LED does not turn green, clean the feeler unit and retry. If testing remains unsuccessful, stop using the machine and contact Festool service.</p>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <h3>Before Starting</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Check that the drive unit with the saw blade correctly and fully swivels back up into its initial position in the protective housing.</li>
        <li>Check the plunging mechanism prior to use.</li>
        <li>Check that the saw blade is securely in place.</li>
        <li>Check that the KickbackStop is functioning properly.</li>
        <li>Ensure the rotary knob [1-3] is tightened.</li>
        <li>Ensure the extractor hose and mains cable will not snag during the cut.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Switching On and Off</h3>
      <p>Slide the switch-on lock [1-13] upwards and press the on/off switch [1-14] (press = ON / release = OFF). The saw unit can then be moved downwards, causing the saw blade to emerge from the protective cover.</p>

      <h3>Sawing Along the Scribe Mark</h3>
      <p>The gauge marker [7-2] displays the cutting line for 0&deg; and 45&deg; cuts (without a guide rail).</p>

      <h3>Cutting Sections</h3>
      <p>Position the machine with the front part of the saw table on the workpiece, switch on, push down to the set cutting depth, and push forward in the cutting direction.</p>

      <h3>Plunge Cuts (Sawing Cut-Outs)</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> To avoid kickbacks, always position the machine with the rear edge of the saw table against a fixed stop. When working with the guide rail, position the machine at the FS-RSP kickback stop clamped to the guide rail.
      </div>
      <ol>
        <li>Place the machine on the workpiece and position it at a stop.</li>
        <li>Switch on the machine.</li>
        <li>Slowly push the machine down to the set cutting depth and push forward in the cutting direction.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>The marks [7-1] indicate the absolute front and rear cutting points of the saw blade when using the saw at maximum cutting depth with the guide rail.</p>

      <h3>Gypsum and Cement-Bound Fibreboards</h3>
      <p>Due to the high volume of dust, use the cover ABSA-TS55/60 (accessory) mounted at the side of the protective cover, along with a Festool mobile dust extractor.</p>

      <h3>Acoustic Warning Signals</h3>
      <p>A series of beeps sounds and the machine switches off when overloaded. Reduce the load on the machine to resume operation.</p>

      <h2>Dust Extraction</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> Health hazard posed by dust. Always work with an extractor. Only use a dust extractor designed to collect the specific type of dust from the material being cut. Follow OSHA and NFPA regulations.
      </div>

      <h3>Independent Extraction (Dust Collection Bag)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Secure the connection piece [6-2] of the dust collection bag [6-3] at the extractor connector [6-1] with a clockwise rotation.</li>
        <li>To empty, remove the connection piece with an anti-clockwise rotation.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>To avoid blockages that may impair safety features, it is better to work with a mobile dust extractor at full suction power.</p>

      <h3>Festool Mobile Dust Extractor</h3>
      <p>A Festool mobile dust extractor with a suction hose diameter of 1-1/16" / 1-17/64" (27/32 mm) or 1-7/16" (36 mm) can be connected to the extractor connector [6-1]. The 36 mm diameter is recommended due to reduced risk of clogging.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>The adapter on a 27 mm suction hose is inserted <em>into</em> the angle adapter [6-4].</li>
        <li>The adapter on a 36 mm suction hose is inserted <em>over</em> the angle adapter [6-4].</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="warning">
        <strong>CAUTION:</strong> A static charge may build up if no antistatic suction hose is used. The user may receive an electric shock and the power tool's electronics may be damaged.
      </div>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/festool-ts60/p12_00.png" alt="Maintenance and adjustment diagram for the Festool TS 60" />
        <figcaption>Maintenance and adjustment reference</figcaption>
      </div>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>WARNING:</strong> Any maintenance or repair work requiring opening of the motor or gear housing must only be carried out by an authorized Customer Service Centre. Always remove the plug from the power supply socket before carrying out any maintenance work.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>Do not use compressed air to clean the electrical tool or internal parts.</li>
        <li>Certain cleaning agents and solvents (gasoline, acetone, MEK, chlorine-based solutions, ammonia) are harmful to plastic parts.</li>
        <li>Damaged safety devices and parts must be properly repaired or replaced in a recognized specialist workshop.</li>
        <li>Check the condition and functioning of recuperating springs that push the drive mechanism into the upper protected end positions.</li>
        <li>Keep cooling air openings in the housing clean and free of blockages.</li>
        <li>Use an extractor on all openings to remove wood chips and splinters. Never open the protective lid [1-23].</li>
        <li>When working with plaster-/cement-bonded fibreboards, clean the vents and on/off switch using dry, oil-free compressed air to prevent gypsum dust buildup.</li>
        <li>Check all warnings on the tool for readability and completeness. Replace missing or illegible warnings.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Reconditioned Saw Blades</h3>
      <p>Use the adjusting screw [9-1] to precisely set the cutting depth for reconditioned (resharpened) saw blades:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Set the cutting depth stop [9-2] to 0 mm (with guide rail).</li>
        <li>Unlock the saw unit and push it downwards as far as the stop.</li>
        <li>Screw the adjusting screw [9-1] in until the saw blade contacts the workpiece.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Saw Table Alignment</h3>
      <p>The saw table must be on an even surface when adjusting the cutting angle. If the saw table wobbles, the setting must be implemented again.</p>

      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Problem</th><th>Possible Cause</th><th>Solution</th></tr>
          <tr><td>Machine does not start</td><td>No power supply or faulty cord</td><td>Check mains connection and extension cord</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Machine shuts off during use</td><td>Overload protection triggered</td><td>Reduce load, allow motor to cool, then restart</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Reduced power during operation</td><td>Temperature cut-out activated</td><td>Allow motor to cool; power resumes automatically</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Beeping sound, machine stops</td><td>Machine overloaded</td><td>Reduce the load on the machine</td></tr>
          <tr><td>KickbackStop LED flashing orange</td><td>Saw started before feeler wedge contacted workpiece, or saw plate not level</td><td>Reposition the saw so it is completely level on the workpiece or guide rail</td></tr>
          <tr><td>KickbackStop LED flashing red</td><td>KickbackStop function triggered</td><td>Release switch, wait for LED to stop flashing, determine cause (see KickbackStop section)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>KickbackStop triggers repeatedly</td><td>Uneven workpiece surface</td><td>Consider deactivating KickbackStop for that cut (see Working without KickbackStop)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>KickbackStop test fails</td><td>Contaminated feeler unit</td><td>Clean the feeler unit; if test still fails, contact Festool service</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Speed cannot be regulated / no smooth start-up</td><td>Defective electronics</td><td>Stop using the machine. Contact Festool service</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Saw table wobbles</td><td>Uneven surface or misaligned angle</td><td>Place on even surface and readjust cutting angle</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

